{"analytics_identifier":null,"base_path":"/government/history/past-prime-ministers/henry-john-temple-3rd-viscount-palmerston","content_id":"3ab47f90-cd6c-44d2-bb9b-8ef3b0e6e3ab","description":"“The function of government is to calm, rather than to excite agitation.”","details":{"body":"<div class=\"govspeak\"><p>Lord Palmerston became enormously popular thanks to his assertive and ‘manly’ foreign policy which proclaimed Britain’s values as a model for the world to follow. He served in government for 46 years.</p>\n\n<p>Although he generally avoided controversial domestic reforms, Palmerston was instrumental in getting Parliament to approve the creation of the Divorce Court in 1857. Before this, people wanting a divorce had had to get a private act of Parliament passed.</p>\n\n<p>Read more about Lord Palmerston on the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"https://history.blog.gov.uk/2016/04/07/lord-palmerston/\" class=\"govuk-link\">History of government blog</a>.</p>\n</div>","born":"20 October 1784, Westminster, London","dates_in_office":[{"end_year":1858,"start_year":1855},{"end_year":1865,"start_year":1859}],"died":"18 October 1865, Brocket Hall, Hertfordshire","interesting_facts":"Florence Nightingale said of Palmerston after his death; “Though he made a joke when asked to do the right thing he always did it. He was so much more in earnest than he appeared, he did not do himself justice.”","major_acts":"Government of India Bill 1858: transferring control of the East India Company to the Crown.","political_party":"Whig and Liberal"},"document_type":"historic_appointment","first_published_at":"2023-01-19T17:38:31+00:00","links":{"available_translations":[{"api_path":"/api/content/government/history/past-prime-ministers/henry-john-temple-3rd-viscount-palmerston","api_url":"https://www.gov.uk/api/content/government/history/past-prime-ministers/henry-john-temple-3rd-viscount-palmerston","base_path":"/government/history/past-prime-ministers/henry-john-temple-3rd-viscount-palmers